answers.answer: Yes,  there are and I rarely see them mentioned on this board.If you're not full term yet and want to get labor started early,  warm buttermilk is a good way to start labor contractions.  Canned beets,   too,  work.If that doesn't work clipping your mails very short often starts contractions.Last,  holding ice in your hands for as long as you can stand it can bring on contractions.If none of this stuff works,  you might just want to wait until the baby is full term and labor begins naturally.

I was just reading about the pinneaple juice as well as mango and papaya....thank you for your answer it is appreciated.

To get enough of the enzyme that people ***think*** may start labor, you would have to eat 7-10 WHOLE *as in skin and all* pineapples.Mango and papaya are the same as pineapple.Do not follow instructions someone else tells your their doctor or midwife gave them. That doctor or midwife have not evaluated you to be able to tell you if the instructions are right for you ad your baby.There is absolutely NOTHING that will start your labor with out your body already starting the process. Your baby is still developing and will be born when he or she is ready. Stop trying to force it to happen. Be a mother and let her finish developing. Trust your body.

Thank you,  wayfunmommy.There ARE things that bring on preterm labor, and they are injurious to the baby and the mother.Incompetent cervix,  serious car wrecks,  food poisoning,  very high fevers,  deteriorating placenta,  placenta detaching from the uterine wall,  preeclampsia,  etc.,  will bring on preterm labor.No one wants any of those awful things.Drinking lots of fruit juice or causing serious diarrhea with castor oil won't bring on labor.Just wait.  Really,  moms,  just wait until your little one is fully baked.
